and earthly space. It recommends that the spatial imagination in the pre-modern world cannot adequately be captured using a linear, militarily framed conceptualization. The scope and varying perspectives on the spatial imagination analyzed in the volume's essays reveal a complex range of aspects that informs how space was designed and utilized. Due to the complexity and advanced scholarly level of the papers, the primary readership will be other scholars and advanced graduate students in history, history of science, geography, art history, religious studies, literature, and, broadly, sinology.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0 uhttps://www.degruyter.com/dg/page/open-access-policy  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Feb 2023) 7aHISTORY / Asia / General.2bisacsh  aPremodern China.  aphysical space.  aspatial imagination.1 aHsu-Tang, H.M. Agnes, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLeung, Vincent S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLycas, Alexis, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMorgan, Daniel Patrick, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPagenstecher Olberding, Garret, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPagenstecher Olberding, Garret, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aPing, Foong, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPowers, Martin J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRui Feng, Linda, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2022 Englishz978311099389908iTit